				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\bullet {\rm{OH}}+{\rm{HCN}}\to \bullet {\rm{NCHOH}}\to \bullet {\rm{OCHNH}}$$\end{document}Protonation and electronic disproportionation with another radical species leads to the FA molecule. The fact that addition of oxygen or nitrate, i.e., electron scavengers, had only a minor effect on the yield of FA also suggests that •OH radicals are involved in the mechanism. Radiolysis of aqueous 25 mM NaCN at pH 7 at 2.92 kGy h−1 over a range of dose rates revealed FA as a major product detectable by GC-MS (G = 0.08 molecules/100 eV), corroborating the proposed mechanism of FA formation through an HCN intermediate.
